I didn't expect
that water. It had legs.

434
00:24:51,880 --> 00:24:53,757
A little work,
a little care...

435
00:24:53,840 --> 00:24:56,308
a little imagination,
and it's gonna be great!

436
00:24:56,400 --> 00:24:58,789
It's gonna be fun
fixing it up. You'll see.

437
00:24:58,880 --> 00:25:01,440
I don't know. I've never been
any good at that kind of thing.

438
00:25:01,520 --> 00:25:03,351
-What kind of thing?
-Work.

439
00:25:03,440 --> 00:25:07,672
You can't go into it with that kind of
attitude. You've gotta be more positive.

440
00:25:07,760 --> 00:25:09,796
-I'll try.
-Oh.

441
00:25:10,880 --> 00:25:13,872
A little care,
a little imagination...

442
00:25:13,960 --> 00:25:15,996
and a positive attitude.

443
00:25:18,400 --> 00:25:21,073
What was that?

444
00:25:22,280 --> 00:25:24,111
Nothing, dear.

445
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:55,797
Son of a bitch.

446
00:25:58,880 --> 00:26:00,711
-[Squeals]
-[Yells]

447
00:26:00,800 --> 00:26:02,950
[Screaming]

448
00:26:10,240 --> 00:26:12,629
<i>[Anna Shouting]</i>

449
00:26:12,720 --> 00:26:14,676
<i>[Screaming Continues]</i>

450
00:26:32,800 --> 00:26:35,268
-Oh, Walter!
-The stairs are out!

451
00:26:36,320 --> 00:26:38,709
[Yells]

452
00:26:38,800 --> 00:26:41,189
Honey,
you're on my fingers.

453
00:26:41,280 --> 00:26:43,111
Oh...
[Screaming]

454
00:26:43,200 --> 00:26:44,872
<i>[Crash]</i>

455
00:26:47,800 --> 00:26:49,518
Sorry.

456
00:26:51,120 --> 00:26:53,236
[Kiss]

457
00:26:53,320 --> 00:26:55,959
<i>[Thunderclap]</i>

458
00:26:57,440 --> 00:27:01,479
I'd help you with that, but somebody
stepped on all my fingers.

459
00:27:01,560 --> 00:27:04,996
-I said I was sorry.
-<i>[Thunder Continues]</i>

460
00:27:05,080 --> 00:27:07,514
I didn't expect your fingers
to be on the floor.

461
00:27:07,600 --> 00:27:09,431
I know.
I'm just cranky.

462
00:27:09,520 --> 00:27:12,637
I guess it's having just thrown
$200,000 into the toilet.

463
00:27:12,720 --> 00:27:15,029
Either that
or the intense pain.

464
00:27:15,120 --> 00:27:18,954
It's only the first day.
You're not gonna give up on it already.

465
00:27:19,040 --> 00:27:21,793
-Oh, yes. Yes, I am.
-Oh, no.

466
00:27:21,880 --> 00:27:24,155
No, you're not.
I'm not gonna let you.

467
00:27:24,240 --> 00:27:27,073
There's a chance we could fob it off
on the Cheap Girls.

468
00:27:27,160 --> 00:27:29,230
We're not
going to sell it.

469
00:27:29,320 --> 00:27:31,151
The land, at least,
has got to be worth something.

470
00:27:31,240 --> 00:27:34,232
The house
is going to be great!

471
00:27:34,320 --> 00:27:36,880
Yeah, if we can peel
the rind off it.

472
00:27:36,960 --> 00:27:41,272
-What?
-It's a lemon, honey, let's face it.

473
00:27:41,360 --> 00:27:43,237
You can't just quit.

474
00:27:43,320 --> 00:27:46,437
I'm a quitter,
and I'm not ready to quit yet.

475
00:27:46,520 --> 00:27:48,351
<i>[Walter]</i>
<i>Why not?</i>

476
00:27:48,440 --> 00:27:51,352
-<i>[Anna] Commitment.</i>
-<i>[Thunderclap]</i>

477
00:27:51,440 --> 00:27:54,637
<i>[Walter]</i>
<i>Oh. That.</i>

478
00:27:54,720 --> 00:27:57,109
<i>You're right.</i>
<i>The house is gonna be great.</i>

479
00:27:57,200 --> 00:27:59,668
-<i>I promise.</i>
-<i>[Kiss]</i>

480
00:28:00,920 --> 00:28:03,309
<i>[Thunder Continues]</i>

481
00:28:03,400 --> 00:28:06,198
<i>[Water Pouring]</i>

482
00:28:16,040 --> 00:28:17,758
-[Both Grunting]
-Lady, this is impossible.

483
00:28:17,840 --> 00:28:20,991
-<i>[Anna] Oh, nonsense.</i>
<i>You're doing fine.</i>
-I feel like I'm gonna die.

484
00:28:21,080 --> 00:28:23,913
You're not going to die.
I'm holding the ladder.

485
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:27,390
If you fall,
land on the mattress.

486
00:28:27,480 --> 00:28:30,870
Hello. Yes. Yes. We're having some
problems with our plumbing, and I was...

487
00:28:30,960 --> 00:28:33,155
-<i>[Man] I can't move.</i>
-Fielding. Walter Fielding.

488
00:28:33,240 --> 00:28:35,231
-<i>[Men Grunting]</i>
-<i>[Anna] Stop being a baby.</i>
<i>You're nearly there.</i>

489
00:28:35,320 --> 00:28:37,470
There's no reason why
you should've heard of me.

490
00:28:37,560 --> 00:28:39,437
<i>I don't have</i>
<i>any references. I just...</i>

491
00:28:39,520 --> 00:28:43,115
-Somebody here call a carpenter?
-Oh, yes. We did.

492
00:28:43,200 --> 00:28:45,634
<i>[Walter]</i>
<i>Yale. Yeah.</i>

493
00:28:45,720 --> 00:28:48,075
-<i>Don't let go of the ladder!</i>
-I wasn't really holding it, anyway.

494
00:28:48,160 --> 00:28:50,515
How much
do I make a year?

495
00:28:50,600 --> 00:28:53,797
Uh, how much
do you make a year?

496
00:28:53,880 --> 00:28:55,711
Really?

497
00:28:55,800 --> 00:28:58,519
-<i>No. No, that's not a Jewish name.</i>
-You're kidding, right?

498
00:28:58,600 --> 00:29:00,431
<i>Get out of my life,</i>
<i>would you?</i>

499
00:29:00,520 --> 00:29:03,592
-<i>[Anna] Don't touch me, pig!</i>
-<i>[Man] Oh, you're cute</i>
<i>when you're mad.</i>

500
00:29:03,680 --> 00:29:05,511
-<i>I'm serious. Get away from me.</i>
-Hey!

501
00:29:05,600 --> 00:29:08,433
-<i>Stop it!</i>
-Hey, let go of her! That's my wife!

502
00:29:08,520 --> 00:29:10,351
Oh, yeah?
Well, I'm sorry.

503
00:29:10,440 --> 00:29:12,317
<i>She didn't say nothin'</i>
<i>about being married.</i>

504
00:29:12,400 --> 00:29:14,914
I just thought she was
good-lookin' wool.

505
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:18,595
<i>This animal attacked me!</i>
<i>I didn't say anything about anything.</i>

506
00:29:18,680 --> 00:29:20,511
Look, I don't wanna
cause trouble.

507
00:29:20,600 --> 00:29:23,353
If I came on a little strong,
I'm sorry, okay?

508
00:29:23,440 --> 00:29:25,874
-No, it's not okay.
-Just get out of here.

509
00:29:25,960 --> 00:29:29,316
Well, okay.
If that's what you want.

510
00:29:29,400 --> 00:29:31,231
I think we should call
the police.

511
00:29:31,320 --> 00:29:33,595
Hey, let's not
get nuts here.

512
00:29:33,680 --> 00:29:35,557
-[Sighing]
-Who are you anyway?

513
00:29:35,640 --> 00:29:40,156
Art Shirk. I'm the carpenter.
I think we spoke on the phone.

514
00:29:40,240 --> 00:29:43,391
-You're the carpenter?
-Yeah. Well, I guess I'll be going.

515
00:29:43,480 --> 00:29:46,756
Oh, wait a minute! Just wait a minute.
Maybe we can clear this up.

516
00:29:46,840 --> 00:29:49,877
<i>Clear this up?</i>
<i>What are you doing? He tried...</i>

517
00:29:49,960 --> 00:29:52,679
I know, but he's supposed to be
a really good carpenter.

518
00:29:52,760 --> 00:29:55,320
-He tried to attack me.
-He just thought you were
good-lookin' wool...

519
00:29:55,400 --> 00:29:57,231
an attractive woman.

520
00:29:57,320 --> 00:30:00,551
-<i>He didn't know who you were.</i>
-I don't know who <i>you</i> are.

521
00:30:00,640 --> 00:30:03,950
[Chuckling]
Look, uh...

522
00:30:04,040 --> 00:30:07,316
do you know how hard it is to find
a really good carpenter?

523
00:30:07,400 --> 00:30:10,073
Besides, I think
he's got a brother who's a plumber.

524
00:30:10,160 --> 00:30:12,833
-Really? A brother who's a plumber?
-I think so.

525
00:30:12,920 --> 00:30:16,356
-Do you think I should sleep with him?
-Maybe just this once.

526
00:30:16,440 --> 00:30:20,115
[Chuckling]
I think I'm going to start dinner.

527
00:30:20,200 --> 00:30:22,156
<i>The house</i>
<i>is gonna be great.</i>

528
00:30:23,800 --> 00:30:25,677
Great.

529
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:28,831
Great!

530
00:30:28,920 --> 00:30:31,718
-Hey, I'm sorry about that...
-Oh, it's all right.

531
00:30:31,800 --> 00:30:34,030
You'll have plenty
of opportunities to make it up to us.

532
00:30:34,120 --> 00:30:36,315
You know, usually a woman
calls a carpenter...

533
00:30:36,400 --> 00:30:38,470
she's lookin' for
the old "hammer and nail."

534
00:30:38,560 --> 00:30:40,790
-And I don't mean...
-Yeah, I know what you mean.

535
00:30:40,880 --> 00:30:43,678
<i>Hey, buddy,</i>
<i>did you really buy this house?</i>

536
00:30:43,760 --> 00:30:45,637
-Yes, I did.
-<i>[Men Snickering]</i>

537
00:30:45,720 --> 00:30:47,631
[Both Laughing]

538
00:30:55,760 --> 00:30:58,558
<i>[Gas Hissing]</i>

539
00:31:06,240 --> 00:31:08,310
Now,
what was over there?

540
00:31:08,400 --> 00:31:12,154
The stairs. It began right there
and it curved all the way...

541
00:31:12,240 --> 00:31:15,994
-<i>[Gas Hissing Continues]</i>
-[Both Sniffing]

542
00:31:17,400 --> 00:31:19,277
Oh, my God!

543
00:31:21,640 --> 00:31:23,995
No, don't!

544
00:31:24,080 --> 00:31:26,640
-[Pilot Light Ignites]
-What's the matter?

545
00:31:28,840 --> 00:31:30,956
I was just
lighting the oven.

546
00:31:31,040 --> 00:31:35,033
Just lighting... You could've
been killed! We could've all died!

547
00:31:35,120 --> 00:31:36,951
Oh, well,
thank you very much.

548
00:31:37,040 --> 00:31:38,871
I'm not completely helpless
in the kitchen.

549
00:31:38,960 --> 00:31:40,837
I do know how
to light an oven.

550
00:31:40,920 --> 00:31:43,309
Well, yeah, but...

551
00:31:43,400 --> 00:31:46,790
-You mean this thing works?
-<i>So far, so good.</i>

552
00:31:46,880 --> 00:31:49,599
Well, it's amazing.
What about the, uh...

553
00:31:49,680 --> 00:31:51,511
-What do you call these?
-The burners.

554
00:31:51,600 --> 00:31:55,673
-I haven't tried them yet.
-Maybe we shouldn't press our luck.

555
00:31:55,760 --> 00:31:58,069
-Wanna see the refrigerator?
-No.

556
00:31:59,120 --> 00:32:01,634
Water?

557
00:32:01,720 --> 00:32:04,951
-[Grinding, Squeaking]
-No water.

558
00:32:05,040 --> 00:32:07,998
We've got gas and electricity, though.
That's two out of three.

559
00:32:08,080 --> 00:32:10,150
Art's calling his brother.
Oh, good news.

560
00:32:10,240 --> 00:32:12,071
You're not gonna have
to sleep with him.

561
00:32:12,160 --> 00:32:15,118
Just a little dinner,
some dancing.

562
00:32:15,200 --> 00:32:18,397
-How long do you think all that'll take?
-Two weeks.

563
00:32:18,480 --> 00:32:21,278
Really? That's all?
When do you think you could start?

564
00:32:21,360 --> 00:32:23,351
Just as soon
as your cheque clears.

565
00:32:23,440 --> 00:32:26,352
Couldn't you at least hang the door?
I've got enough cash for that.

566
00:32:26,440 --> 00:32:28,635
Haven't got
the right materials.

567
00:32:28,720 --> 00:32:31,314
Wood's rotten.
Won't hold a screw.

568
00:32:32,360 --> 00:32:35,238
Which reminds me:

569
00:32:35,320 --> 00:32:39,029
-I'm late for my next job.
-[Engine Starts]

570
00:32:39,120 --> 00:32:41,839
-If you know what I mean.
-<i>[Car Radio] # I gotta be me #</i>

571
00:32:41,920 --> 00:32:45,196
-<i># I gotta be me #</i>
-Yeah, I know what you mean.

572
00:32:45,280 --> 00:32:48,829
<i># What else can I be ##</i>

573
00:32:49,160 --> 00:32:51,674
<i>[Door Opens, Closes]</i>

574
00:32:51,760 --> 00:32:54,672
<i>[Coughing] In spite of</i>
<i>all the problems...</i>

575
00:32:54,760 --> 00:32:57,797
in spite of the prospect of indentured
servitude for the rest of my life...

576
00:32:57,880 --> 00:33:00,075
in debt beyond
my wildest dreams...

577
00:33:00,160 --> 00:33:01,991
I love the house.

578
00:33:02,080 --> 00:33:03,911
So do I.

579
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:05,831
And I love you.

580
00:33:06,920 --> 00:33:09,878
-Life is good.
-<i>## [Violin]</i>

581
00:33:11,160 --> 00:33:12,991
<i>[Door Closes]</i>

582
00:33:13,080 --> 00:33:15,913
<i>## [Continues]</i>

583
00:33:31,600 --> 00:33:34,990
-<i>[Insects Buzzing]</i>
-<i>[Birds Chirping]</i>

584
00:33:35,080 --> 00:33:36,911
<i>[Zipper Zips Down]</i>

585
00:33:38,800 --> 00:33:41,758
<i>[Water Pouring]</i>

586
00:33:46,440 --> 00:33:48,351
Prostate trouble?

587
00:33:49,920 --> 00:33:51,751
-<i>[Water Stops]</i>
-<i>[Zipper Zips Up]</i>

588
00:34:09,640 --> 00:34:12,552
<i>[Birds Chirping Loudly]</i>

589
00:34:14,200 --> 00:34:16,031
<i>[Door Opens]</i>

590
00:34:16,120 --> 00:34:17,951
-<i>[Door Closes]</i>
-<i>[Footsteps Approaching]</i>

591
00:34:18,040 --> 00:34:20,156
<i>Well, that was fast.</i>

592
00:34:20,240 --> 00:34:23,038
We have very weak trees.

593
00:34:23,120 --> 00:34:25,475
"Weak trees"?

594
00:34:25,560 --> 00:34:28,632
<i>[Doorbell Chimes,</i>
<i>Winds Down]</i>

595
00:34:28,720 --> 00:34:30,836
I guess that's the door.

596
00:34:30,920 --> 00:34:34,230
Hurry, don't let it ring again.
[Sighs]

597
00:34:35,880 --> 00:34:37,711
Wait!

598
00:34:37,800 --> 00:34:39,631
-You Fielding?
-Right!

599
00:34:39,720 --> 00:34:41,551
My brother Art
recommended you.

600
00:34:41,640 --> 00:34:44,438
-I don't usually take jobs in this area.
-I'm glad you can make an exception.

601
00:34:44,520 --> 00:34:47,034
-Let's not get ahead of ourselves, okay?
-I'm sorry.

602
00:34:47,120 --> 00:34:49,918
-Where should we start?
-Well, you could offer me a drink.

603
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:51,831
I don't know
where my manners are.

604
00:34:51,920 --> 00:34:55,276
Here it is, nearly 11:30.
You must be parched.

605
00:34:58,960 --> 00:35:01,758
<i>What? Wait a minute! We haven't even</i>
<i>talked about the plumbing yet!</i>

606
00:35:01,840 --> 00:35:04,559
And we're not going to,
not with your attitude.

607
00:35:04,640 --> 00:35:07,108
Oh, saving the good scotch
for the company, are we?

608
00:35:07,200 --> 00:35:09,031
No wonder you've been turned down
by every plumber in the valley.

609
00:35:09,120 --> 00:35:11,350
-That's not true!
-Don't make it worse by lying.

610
00:35:11,440 --> 00:35:14,830
I'm not lying!
I haven't tried everybody yet.

611
00:35:14,920 --> 00:35:16,797
Please,
you gotta help me!

612
00:35:16,880 --> 00:35:19,269
I don't know.

613
00:35:19,360 --> 00:35:22,272
Write me a cheque quick,
before I come to my senses. Five grand.

614
00:35:22,360 --> 00:35:25,591
-Five grand... Five thousand dollars?
-That's just a deposit.

615
00:35:25,680 --> 00:35:27,511
You didn't even...
Well...

616
00:35:27,600 --> 00:35:31,832
I'm not tryin' to tell you your business,
but you haven't even looked at my pipes.

617
00:35:31,920 --> 00:35:34,878
I looked at them three years ago.
You figure they've improved with age?

618
00:35:34,960 --> 00:35:37,269
-[Engine Starts]
-<i>[Car Radio] # Me #</i>

619
00:35:37,360 --> 00:35:40,636
<i># I gotta be me #</i>

620
00:35:40,720 --> 00:35:46,511
<i># What else can I be</i>
<i>but what I am ##</i>

621
00:35:54,000 --> 00:35:56,275
Prep school.
[Clears Throat]

622
00:35:56,360 --> 00:35:59,830
Yale.
Phi Beta Kappa.

623
00:35:59,920 --> 00:36:03,595
Four years of law school,
law review.

624
00:36:03,680 --> 00:36:05,750
Are you all right?

625
00:36:05,840 --> 00:36:08,673
Oh, yeah, I'm fine.

626
00:36:08,760 --> 00:36:10,751
The secret is not to,
uh, look down.

627
00:36:10,840 --> 00:36:13,308
Oh, why did you
say that?

628
00:36:13,400 --> 00:36:15,516
Look down?
It's a secret.

629
00:36:15,600 --> 00:36:17,431
I was fine
till you said that.

630
00:36:17,520 --> 00:36:19,351
I'm sorry.
You're doin' great.

631
00:36:19,440 --> 00:36:22,193
-Mm-hmm.
-Just great.

632
00:36:27,480 --> 00:36:30,472
If you don't mind,
I'm gonna share this bath with you...

633
00:36:30,560 --> 00:36:32,596
-because I can't do this a second time.
-Ooh!

634
00:36:32,680 --> 00:36:34,989
I think that's
a swell idea.

635
00:36:35,080 --> 00:36:39,312
That way you can save your energy
for more worthwhile causes.

636
00:36:39,400 --> 00:36:41,231
Mmm.

637
00:36:43,360 --> 00:36:45,920
Mmm.

638
00:36:46,000 --> 00:36:48,719
Would you get the rest
of the water, okay?

639
00:36:48,800 --> 00:36:50,916
-[Chuckling]
-[Sighing]

640
00:36:51,360 --> 00:36:54,716
Hi, this is Julia Child with a tip
on making crepes Suzette...

641
00:36:54,800 --> 00:36:58,190
<i>that marvellous flaming dessert</i>
<i>that you do at the table.</i>

642
00:36:58,280 --> 00:37:02,398
<i>You need a nice flaming set-up.</i>
<i>I've got a heat source there.</i>

643
00:37:02,480 --> 00:37:04,311
<i>There's an attractive pan.</i>

644
00:37:04,400 --> 00:37:10,794
<i>In the pan I have a mixture</i>
<i>of sugar, butter, orangejuice</i>
<i>and grated orange peel.</i>

645
00:37:10,880 --> 00:37:14,873
<i>I'm taking a crepe,</i>
<i>and I'm bathing it in this mixture...</i>

646
00:37:14,960 --> 00:37:18,270
-[Crackling]
-<i>[TV: Child Continues]</i>

647
00:37:19,520 --> 00:37:21,829
<i>[Loud Crackling]</i>

648
00:37:26,760 --> 00:37:30,036
<i>[TV: Child] I like to use</i>
<i>a no-stick pan and heat until water...</i>

649
00:37:30,120 --> 00:37:32,429
-<i>[Tiles Breaking]</i>
-<i>[Electricity Crackling]</i>

650
00:37:35,960 --> 00:37:38,269
<i>[Blender Whirring]</i>

651
00:37:38,360 --> 00:37:41,352
<i>[TV: Child Continues]</i>

652
00:37:54,320 --> 00:37:57,073
<i>... and on goes</i>
<i>some nice brandy.</i>

653
00:37:57,160 --> 00:38:01,358
Let it bubble up well,
and then dip it into your flames...

654
00:38:06,320 --> 00:38:08,151
Ow!

655
00:38:34,960 --> 00:38:37,758
Little problem in the kitchen.
Nothing trivial.

656
00:38:41,640 --> 00:38:43,756
Well,
the turkey's done.

657
00:38:43,840 --> 00:38:46,070
So is the kitchen.

658
00:38:46,160 --> 00:38:49,152
Actually, it's a little overdone
for my taste.

659
00:38:49,240 --> 00:38:51,515
Let's not
go there again.

660
00:38:51,600 --> 00:38:55,195
-You don't want to
tell me what happened?
-No, I don't.

661
00:38:55,280 --> 00:38:59,796
-I just want to relax
in a nice lukewarm bath.
-What about this?

662
00:38:59,880 --> 00:39:02,474
<i>[Walter] I don't think</i>
<i>that can hurt us any more.</i>

663
00:39:11,160 --> 00:39:13,993
[Laughing]

664
00:39:25,920 --> 00:39:28,718
[Laughing Hysterically]

665
00:39:47,480 --> 00:39:50,313
What are you doing?

666
00:39:50,400 --> 00:39:52,516
-Save yourself.
-What?

667
00:39:52,600 --> 00:39:54,431
I'm a menace
to anything I touch.

668
00:39:54,520 --> 00:39:57,432
The Surgeon General's warning
should be tattooed across my forehead.

669
00:39:57,520 --> 00:40:00,114
"Walter Fielding is dangerous
to your health. Don't touch him."

670
00:40:00,200 --> 00:40:02,919
-<i>Save yourself.</i>
-I can't.

671
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:05,753
-I've tried, but I love Walter Fielding.
-No.

672
00:40:05,840 --> 00:40:08,957
-I can't give him up.
I'm hopelessly addicted.
-No.

673
00:40:09,040 --> 00:40:12,510
You must think of yourself!
I am sinking fast into the money pit...

674
00:40:12,600 --> 00:40:14,431
and I don't want to
drag you down with me.

675
00:40:14,520 --> 00:40:17,751
-Save yourself
while there's still time.
-Walter, brighten up.

676
00:40:17,840 --> 00:40:21,958
-I hate seeing you like this.
-I hate being like this. I'm a disaster.

677
00:40:22,040 --> 00:40:26,909
These are estimates from legitimate
contractors for repairs on the pit.

678
00:40:27,000 --> 00:40:30,629
Those that will actually come out here
are so expensive, I can't talk about it.

679
00:40:30,720 --> 00:40:32,836
Let's not talk about it.

680
00:40:32,920 --> 00:40:34,911
I've just given
our last $5,000...

681
00:40:35,000 --> 00:40:38,356
our last 5,000 borrowed dollars...
to the Shirks.

682
00:40:38,440 --> 00:40:41,989
Walter, I don't mean
to be questioning you, but why...

683
00:40:42,080 --> 00:40:43,911
They were willing to take it!

684
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:46,594
The legitimate people wanted
four times as much just to say "hello."

685
00:40:46,680 --> 00:40:48,989
So it's the Shirks.
That's not so bad.

686
00:40:49,080 --> 00:40:50,911
Well, that's if they show up.

687
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:53,798
Just because they showed up
to collect the money...

688
00:40:53,880 --> 00:40:56,030
is no guarantee that
they'll show up to do the work.

689
00:40:56,120 --> 00:40:59,590
And if they do,
I can't pay for it!

690
00:40:59,680 --> 00:41:02,717
-I'm going to help you.
-Do you have a gun?

691
00:41:02,800 --> 00:41:06,873
"Here lies Walter Fielding.
He bought a house, and it killed him."

692
00:41:06,960 --> 00:41:08,951
If I could raise some more money,
would that help?

693
00:41:09,040 --> 00:41:11,235
-Depends on how you're gonna
raise the money.
-Mmm.

694
00:41:11,320 --> 00:41:13,629
-I think I know how.
-I <i>know</i> you know how.

695
00:41:13,720 --> 00:41:17,429
Just stop.
I've got some things I can sell.

696
00:41:17,520 --> 00:41:21,069
I don't wanna talk about money
or the house any more tonight.

697
00:41:21,160 --> 00:41:24,675
Neither do I. We could just skip town,
borrow some bus fare.

698
00:41:24,760 --> 00:41:29,117
Or we could hitchhike,
hit the open road.

699
00:41:29,200 --> 00:41:31,191
Everything's gonna be
just fine.

700
00:41:31,280 --> 00:41:34,556
-You'll see. Trust me.
-How?

701
00:41:34,640 --> 00:41:38,030
-Don't you trust me?
-It's not that. It's just that...

702
00:41:40,280 --> 00:41:43,113
We'll think of somethin'.
Who cares?

703
00:41:53,160 --> 00:41:55,958
<i>[Engines Rumbling]</i>

704
00:42:16,560 --> 00:42:20,394
-What's happening?
-Well, stay here. I'll find out.

705
00:42:27,160 --> 00:42:29,993
[Men Chattering,
Shouting]

706
00:42:37,880 --> 00:42:41,839
Hi. You must be
Mr Fielding. [Laughing]

707
00:42:41,920 --> 00:42:44,912
-Yeah. Yeah. Who...
-I'm from Shirk Brothers.

708
00:42:45,000 --> 00:42:48,117
Your number came up in the drawing
this morning. We work today!

709
00:42:48,200 --> 00:42:50,919
Oh, that's great.
That's... Where is Brad?

710
00:42:51,000 --> 00:42:53,116
Oh, South of France,
I think.

711
00:42:53,200 --> 00:42:55,668
Uh, don't...
Shouldn't he be here?

712
00:42:55,760 --> 00:42:59,548
Brad is the executive plumber.
We do all the work.

713
00:42:59,640 --> 00:43:01,471
We're just about
to get started.

714
00:43:01,560 --> 00:43:04,791
You're free to watch if you want,
though I wouldn't recommend it.

715
00:43:04,880 --> 00:43:07,599
-Are there any living things in there?
-Well, my girlfr...

716
00:43:07,680 --> 00:43:11,434
-My wife. What the hell.
-Oh, I'd get her out.

717
00:43:11,520 --> 00:43:14,671
Hold it, fellas. Just a second.
There's a woman inside there.

718
00:43:14,760 --> 00:43:16,591
Hold it!
Come on!

719
00:43:16,680 --> 00:43:21,117
Hey, come on! Wait a minute, fellas,
there's a lady inside there.

720
00:43:21,200 --> 00:43:23,714
H-Here! Here she...

721
00:43:23,800 --> 00:43:27,554
H-Here you go. Okay?
Are you all right?

722
00:43:27,640 --> 00:43:30,473
-Yes, thank you.
-Is everything out?

723
00:43:30,560 --> 00:43:33,393
-Yeah.
-[Engine Starts]

724
00:43:33,480 --> 00:43:36,517
-Okay. Have a nice day!
-Who are they?

725
00:43:36,600 --> 00:43:38,079
-The plumbers.
-Are you sure?

726
00:43:38,120 --> 00:43:41,271
No, and I don't care. I'm just thrilled
to see somebody actually working.

727
00:43:41,320 --> 00:43:44,392
Mrs Fielding,
don't worry about a thing.

728
00:43:44,480 --> 00:43:47,313
<i>[Chattering,</i>
<i>Shouting Continues]</i>

729
00:43:47,400 --> 00:43:50,676
-Okay, guys, let's do it!
-Yeah!

730
00:43:58,200 --> 00:44:02,751
<i>[Anna] In our settlement you listed</i>
<i>the value of that painting at $ 100,000.</i>

731
00:44:02,840 --> 00:44:04,717
I'll sell it
to you for 75.

732
00:44:04,800 --> 00:44:06,631
[Max] That painting
doesn't interest me.

733
00:44:06,720 --> 00:44:08,551
Yes, it does.
You love that painting.

734
00:44:08,640 --> 00:44:10,471
That's the only reason
I took it.

735
00:44:10,560 --> 00:44:12,391
All you want
to talk about is money.

736
00:44:12,480 --> 00:44:16,359
Let's talk about love and sex.
Forget love, let's just talk about sex.

737
00:44:16,440 --> 00:44:18,510
Max, I'm desperate.
I need money.

738
00:44:18,600 --> 00:44:21,160
I need new plumbing.
I need new appliances.

739
00:44:21,240 --> 00:44:24,710
-A new staircase, Max.
-Stop, please. Too boring.

740
00:44:24,800 --> 00:44:30,079
-Plastering, landscaping,
painting, a roof.
-Too middle class. Stop.

741
00:44:30,160 --> 00:44:34,392
New floors, new tiles,
new fixtures in the bathroom.

742
00:44:34,480 --> 00:44:36,710
Okay, okay, I'll buy it.
I'll give you the money.

743
00:44:36,800 --> 00:44:38,870
Only, please, God,
stop!

744
00:44:38,960 --> 00:44:43,875
Thank you, Max.
Sometimes you can be very sweet.

745
00:44:43,960 --> 00:44:46,076
I know.

746
00:44:46,160 --> 00:44:49,118
-How do I look in this?
-Oh, beautiful.

747
00:44:49,200 --> 00:44:53,512
You look beautiful
in everything. Mm-hmm.

748
00:44:54,280 --> 00:44:56,589
Hi!

749
00:44:58,920 --> 00:45:00,751
Hi.

750
00:45:00,840 --> 00:45:02,398
[Engine Sputters,
Dies]

751
00:45:02,480 --> 00:45:04,311
What happened?

752
00:45:04,400 --> 00:45:07,198
It was no picnic, but those boys
are work animals.

753
00:45:07,280 --> 00:45:10,829
-Well, everything looks
pretty well under control.
-It does?

754
00:45:10,920 --> 00:45:13,673
<i>Well, not to the layman's eyes,</i>
<i>of course.</i>

755
00:45:13,760 --> 00:45:17,036
They completely ripped up
our house!

756
00:45:17,120 --> 00:45:20,396
<i>They sure as hell did!</i>
<i>They ripped the guts out of it!</i>

757
00:45:20,480 --> 00:45:23,278
They're work animals,
I'm telling you!

758
00:45:23,360 --> 00:45:25,191
Look at
those holes!

759
00:45:25,280 --> 00:45:27,111
Then you got
your gravel piles...

760
00:45:27,200 --> 00:45:29,031
your sand piles,
your scrap piles.

761
00:45:29,120 --> 00:45:30,951
-Animals!
-Animals.

762
00:45:31,040 --> 00:45:34,237
Well, I like a good conversation
as well as anybody, but I gotta run.

763
00:45:34,320 --> 00:45:36,629
<i>Hasta pronto,</i>
if you know what I mean.

764
00:45:36,720 --> 00:45:40,474
-Y-You're leaving?
-Well, I ain't movin' in. [Laughing]

765
00:45:40,560 --> 00:45:43,358
But we'll be back
when you get your permits.

766
00:45:43,440 --> 00:45:46,238
Permits? The permit man
was supposed to be here by 4:00.

767
00:45:46,320 --> 00:45:49,118
Oh, he was, but you or your wife
weren't here to meet him.

768
00:45:49,200 --> 00:45:51,031
We weren't?
Anna's not here?

769
00:45:51,120 --> 00:45:52,951
No, no.
I would've noticed.

770
00:45:53,040 --> 00:45:54,871
The permit man
was pretty agitated.

771
00:45:54,960 --> 00:45:56,791
Really steamed his clams.

772
00:45:56,880 --> 00:46:00,634
Said he'd be back
when you grow udders and get milked.

773
00:46:00,720 --> 00:46:02,551
-[Laughs]
-That's a long time.

774
00:46:02,640 --> 00:46:04,471
Yeah. Yeah.

775
00:46:04,560 --> 00:46:08,314
Well, if he ever does come back,
you call me and we'll finish the job.

776
00:46:08,400 --> 00:46:11,358
When I do get the permits,
how long will the job take?

777
00:46:11,440 --> 00:46:13,271
Two weeks.

778
00:46:13,360 --> 00:46:15,191
Two weeks?
Two weeks?

779
00:46:15,280 --> 00:46:18,829
You sound like a parakeet.
"Two weeks? Two weeks?" [Laughs]

780
00:46:18,920 --> 00:46:21,832
Well, uh, two weeks.
It's... It's amazing.

781
00:46:21,920 --> 00:46:23,751
-Amazing, nothing.
-[Engine Starts]

782
00:46:23,840 --> 00:46:26,638
It'll be a regular miracle.
[Continues Laughing]

783
00:46:28,800 --> 00:46:31,598
<i>[Phone Ringing]</i>

784
00:46:33,920 --> 00:46:36,559
-<i>[Ringing Continues]</i>
-[Groans]

785
00:46:39,160 --> 00:46:40,991
[Groans]

786
00:46:43,040 --> 00:46:45,838
<i>[Ringing Continues]</i>

787
00:46:45,920 --> 00:46:47,751
Hello?

788
00:46:47,840 --> 00:46:49,910
Oh, hi there.

789
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:52,309
"Tone"?
My voice has no tone.

790
00:46:52,400 --> 00:46:55,198
Because I'm standing
in a pile of rubble...

791
00:46:55,280 --> 00:46:57,589
and we don't
have the permits to un-rubble it.

792
00:46:57,680 --> 00:47:01,116
"Exaggerating"? Honey, we're living
in Swiss cheese with a door.

793
00:47:01,200 --> 00:47:04,237
"Mozart"? Mozart is dead.
His troubles are over.

794
00:47:04,320 --> 00:47:06,151
Help <i>me!</i>

795
00:47:06,240 --> 00:47:09,038
[Sighs]
All right. I'm sorry.

796
00:47:09,120 --> 00:47:12,999
You're right. If you had to work,
you had to work.

797
00:47:13,080 --> 00:47:14,911
Oh, l-l-I love you too.

798
00:47:15,000 --> 00:47:18,037
Where is the guy's number?
The permit man.

799
00:47:18,120 --> 00:47:19,951
In the den, you think.

800
00:47:20,040 --> 00:47:22,349
I will pick you up
at the station.

801
00:47:22,440 --> 00:47:25,750
Just give me a call
when you get there. [Kissing Sounds]

802
00:47:38,160 --> 00:47:39,991
"Shrapp"?

803
00:47:51,840 --> 00:47:54,149
Is Mr Shrapp in?

804
00:47:54,240 --> 00:47:57,038
Mr Shrapp.
Walter Fielding.

805
00:47:57,120 --> 00:47:59,918
Hey, watch what you say
about my mother, now.

806
00:48:00,000 --> 00:48:02,036
Mr Shrapp,
let's be adults about this.

807
00:48:02,120 --> 00:48:05,237
I'm... Look, I'm very sorry
I wasn't here this afternoon.

808
00:48:05,320 --> 00:48:08,710
My wife was poisoned
and taken to the hospital.

809
00:48:08,800 --> 00:48:10,631
[Taps Foot]

810
00:48:10,720 --> 00:48:13,518
Well, what would
cut any ice with you?

811
00:48:13,600 --> 00:48:16,433
A bribe? Sure.
Can you be here in a half an hour?

812
00:48:17,760 --> 00:48:19,591
All right.

813
00:48:19,680 --> 00:48:21,511
Cash? No problem.

814
00:48:21,600 --> 00:48:23,636
[Dial Tone]

815
00:48:23,920 --> 00:48:25,558
Weasel.

816
00:48:25,640 --> 00:48:28,473
Cash.
Cash, cash, ca...

817
00:48:33,640 --> 00:48:35,517
[Grunts]

818
00:48:36,800 --> 00:48:38,836
[Continues Grunting]
H-Help!

819
00:48:48,920 --> 00:48:51,753
<i>[Walter]</i>
<i># Come on, everybody #</i>

820
00:48:51,840 --> 00:48:54,638
<i># I said</i>
<i>let's play a game #</i>

821
00:48:54,720 --> 00:48:57,678
<i># I bet ya</i>
<i>I can make a rhyme #</i>

822
00:48:57,760 --> 00:49:00,069
# Out of anybody's name #

823
00:49:00,160 --> 00:49:01,991
Anna!
# Anna-Anna, bo-banna #

824
00:49:02,080 --> 00:49:03,752
# Banana-fanna, fo-fanna #

825
00:49:03,840 --> 00:49:06,035
# Fee-fi, mo-manna #

826
00:49:06,120 --> 00:49:07,917
# Anna #

827
00:49:08,000 --> 00:49:09,718
Let's try Brad!

828
00:49:09,800 --> 00:49:11,791
# Brad, Brad, bo-rad
Banana-fanna #

829
00:49:11,880 --> 00:49:13,711
-[Knocks]
-<i>[Walter] Walter!</i>

830
00:49:13,800 --> 00:49:16,394
-Fielding!
-<i># Walter, Walter, bo-balter</i>
<i>Banana-fanna, fo-falter #</i>

831
00:49:16,480 --> 00:49:19,313
# Fee-fi, mo-malter
Walter ##

832
00:49:19,400 --> 00:49:22,198
-<i>[Knocking Continues]</i>
-Hello... [Grunts]

833
00:49:22,280 --> 00:49:24,271
Hello!
Hello! I'm here!

834
00:49:24,360 --> 00:49:26,191
Are you in there,
Fielding?

835
00:49:26,280 --> 00:49:28,111
[Continues Knocking]

836
00:49:28,200 --> 00:49:30,998
Y-Yeah!
l-I'm here.

837
00:49:31,080 --> 00:49:32,911
M-My chest
is constricted.

838
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:36,549
I can't shout.
O-Oww! Oww!

839
00:49:36,640 --> 00:49:38,471
<i>[Walter Groaning]</i>

840
00:49:38,560 --> 00:49:42,519
Okay, Fielding,
I can hear you in there laughing at me.

841
00:49:42,600 --> 00:49:44,909
This is it,
you duck fart!

842
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:48,436
I'm leaving, and I'm never coming back!
Ya hear me, Fielding?

843
00:49:48,520 --> 00:49:51,637
Y-Y-Yes, I hear you!

844
00:49:51,720 --> 00:49:54,154
<i>I'm tearing up</i>
<i>your permit!</i>

845
00:49:54,240 --> 00:49:56,071
There!

846
00:49:56,160 --> 00:49:57,991
Nobody laughs
at Montgomery Shrapp!

847
00:50:00,760 --> 00:50:04,036
<i>[Phone Ringing]</i>

848
00:50:06,440 --> 00:50:08,795
<i>[Ringing Continues]</i>

849
00:50:54,080 --> 00:50:55,911
[Brakes Compress]

850
00:50:56,000 --> 00:50:58,833
<i>[Anna]</i>
<i>Good Lord!</i>

851
00:50:58,920 --> 00:51:01,957
You testin' missiles here,
or what?

852
00:51:02,040 --> 00:51:04,349
The house
is gonna be great.

853
00:51:05,560 --> 00:51:09,792
<i>[Truck Engine Idling,</i>
<i>Horn Blasting]</i>

854
00:51:09,880 --> 00:51:12,678
<i>[Brakes Decompress,</i>
<i>Truck Pulls Away]</i>

855
00:51:19,880 --> 00:51:21,711
<i>[Footsteps]</i>

856
00:51:21,800 --> 00:51:24,872
<i>[Keys Jingling,</i>
<i>Lock Unlocking]</i>

857
00:51:24,960 --> 00:51:26,359
Shh.

858
00:51:26,880 --> 00:51:28,757
<i>[Door Closes]</i>

859
00:51:30,400 --> 00:51:32,914
Oh, my God.

860
00:51:34,880 --> 00:51:36,757
Walter!

861
00:51:36,840 --> 00:51:38,796
Oh!
Oh, A-Anna!

862
00:51:38,880 --> 00:51:42,156
Thank God it's you!
Thank God! Ohh!

863
00:51:42,240 --> 00:51:44,071
Walter?

864
00:51:44,160 --> 00:51:47,436
-<i>Thank God you're here, honey!</i>
-Is that you?

865
00:51:47,520 --> 00:51:49,670
[Laughs]
Is it me?

866
00:51:49,760 --> 00:51:52,558
Ha! Is it me?
[Continues Laughing]

867
00:51:55,360 --> 00:51:58,636
<i>Anna, I've been here so long</i>
<i>I'm hallucinating.</i>

868
00:51:58,720 --> 00:52:01,678
<i>A while ago I thought</i>
<i>the Care Bears were here.</i>

869
00:52:01,760 --> 00:52:03,591
Walter?

870
00:52:03,680 --> 00:52:07,116
<i>Farm animals, or geese and chickens...</i>
<i>[Continues Laughing]</i>

871
00:52:07,200 --> 00:52:09,031
Walter?

872
00:52:09,120 --> 00:52:10,997
Upstairs!

873
00:52:11,080 --> 00:52:12,911
Are you all right?

874
00:52:13,000 --> 00:52:16,549
No, I'm not all right.
Not at all.

875
00:52:18,200 --> 00:52:20,031
No!

876
00:52:20,120 --> 00:52:22,429
-<i>Where are you?</i>
-I'm in the den.

877
00:52:22,520 --> 00:52:25,318
<i>No, you're not.</i>
<i>I was just in there.</i>

878
00:52:25,400 --> 00:52:28,472
I'm in the den. I swear it.
Please believe me.

879
00:52:28,560 --> 00:52:31,597
<i>Will you stop fooling around,</i>
<i>Walter? I'm tired.</i>

880
00:52:31,680 --> 00:52:33,511
I'm right here.

881
00:52:33,600 --> 00:52:35,830
<i>Look, Walter,</i>
<i>enough is enough.</i>

882
00:52:35,920 --> 00:52:38,070
I'm right here!

883
00:52:39,680 --> 00:52:41,716
Where?

884
00:52:41,800 --> 00:52:44,155
In the floor,
behind the chair.

885
00:52:47,520 --> 00:52:50,080
[Laughing]
Ohh!

886
00:52:52,600 --> 00:52:54,750
Oh, laughing.
[Chuckles]

887
00:52:54,840 --> 00:52:57,149
-<i>[Laughing Continues]</i>
-We're laughing.

888
00:52:58,240 --> 00:53:00,071
The permit man was here.

889
00:53:00,160 --> 00:53:02,151
-Oh, that's good.
-No, it's not.

890
00:53:02,240 --> 00:53:05,789
Now tomorrow I've got to
take off work, drive to his office...

891
00:53:05,880 --> 00:53:07,711
and kiss his ass.

892
00:53:07,800 --> 00:53:09,791
-Oh!
-<i>[Thud]</i>

893
00:53:14,360 --> 00:53:17,796
-<i>[Wind Gusting]</i>
-Well, thanks to that fall
we're now the same height.

894
00:53:19,040 --> 00:53:20,871
Yeah, that's much better.

895
00:53:20,960 --> 00:53:22,791
<i>[Wind Gusting]</i>

896
00:53:22,880 --> 00:53:25,678
-So, why did rehearsal run so long?
-That was my fault.

897
00:53:25,760 --> 00:53:30,311
We got off to a late start because I was
haggling with Max over the painting.

898
00:53:30,400 --> 00:53:33,153
How, exactly, would you
define "haggling"?

899
00:53:33,240 --> 00:53:36,835
-What do you mean by that?
-I thought that was my question.

900
00:53:36,920 --> 00:53:38,751
Are you jealous
of Max?

901
00:53:40,320 --> 00:53:42,311
Jealous of Max?

902
00:53:42,400 --> 00:53:44,231
Don't be silly.

903
00:53:44,320 --> 00:53:47,118
Just because he's rich, famous,
good-looking, brilliant.

904
00:53:47,200 --> 00:53:50,317
-I mean, what's he got
that I haven't got?
-Walls.

905
00:53:50,400 --> 00:53:52,231
I feel much better.

906
00:54:04,640 --> 00:54:06,517
Good night, hon.

907
00:54:11,160 --> 00:54:12,991
Good night.

908
00:54:17,480 --> 00:54:20,199
<i>[Shouting, Chattering]</i>

909
00:54:20,280 --> 00:54:24,193
Look out for that thing.
You're gonna fall off of it.

910
00:54:24,280 --> 00:54:26,589
[Shouting,
Chattering Continue]

911
00:54:30,880 --> 00:54:33,519
<i>[Moaning]</i>

912
00:54:33,600 --> 00:54:36,114
[Kissing Sounds,
Moaning Continues]

913
00:54:40,960 --> 00:54:44,999
[Continues Moaning]

914
00:54:45,080 --> 00:54:46,752
Get to work!

915
00:54:46,840 --> 00:54:49,149
[Anna Screaming]

916
00:54:53,880 --> 00:54:56,678
<i>Four months</i>
<i>since I got those permits.</i>

917
00:54:56,760 --> 00:54:59,558
They're not even half done.
They said two weeks for the whole job.

918
00:54:59,640 --> 00:55:02,438
You're telling me this
like I haven't been here.

919
00:55:02,520 --> 00:55:04,351
We're going through
a rough time.

920
00:55:04,440 --> 00:55:08,194
-Let's remember not to
take it out on each other.
-You're right.

921
00:55:08,280 --> 00:55:12,034
You hear about that guy up in the Bronx,
went crazy, thought he was a pigeon?

922
00:55:12,120 --> 00:55:14,918
They found him in the park
throwing bread crumbs at himself.

923
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:17,798
-He was just putting in
a guest bathroom.
-Okay.

924
00:55:17,880 --> 00:55:21,156
So let's be nice to each other.
We're all we've got.

925
00:55:21,240 --> 00:55:23,071
Don't forget
to get the water.

926
00:55:23,160 --> 00:55:25,958
-Haven't I gotten the water
every morning for four months?
-Walter.

927
00:55:26,040 --> 00:55:28,759
-Do I ever forget the water?
-Don't do this. Walter, Walter, Walter!

928
00:55:28,840 --> 00:55:30,717
I'm sorry.

929
00:55:31,880 --> 00:55:33,996
The bucket's
in the hall.

930
00:55:35,080 --> 00:55:37,036
[Muttering]
I know where the bucket is.

931
00:55:37,120 --> 00:55:39,918
You don't have to tell me
where the bucket is.

932
00:55:50,600 --> 00:55:52,909
Stairs!
Ha!

933
00:55:53,000 --> 00:55:55,798
A staircase!
We have stairs!

934
00:55:55,880 --> 00:55:57,757
[Laughing]

935
00:55:59,560 --> 00:56:03,678
Oh, hello, Mr Stairs.
I've missed you.

936
00:56:05,600 --> 00:56:07,716
Anna?
Anna, darling!

937
00:56:07,800 --> 00:56:09,631
<i>Did you</i>
<i>get the water?</i>

938
00:56:09,720 --> 00:56:11,711
We have stairs!

939
00:56:11,800 --> 00:56:14,758
[Laughing]
It's happening, honey.

940
00:56:14,840 --> 00:56:16,671
Everything's
gonna be fixed.

941
00:56:16,760 --> 00:56:19,274
[Sobbing]
We have stairs.

942
00:56:19,360 --> 00:56:21,396
That's terrific.

943
00:56:21,480 --> 00:56:24,677
-<i>Everything's gonna be wonderful.</i>
-Yes.

944
00:56:24,760 --> 00:56:27,069
<i>Sweetheart,</i>
<i>I could really use some water.</i>

945
00:56:27,160 --> 00:56:30,118
[Sniffling]
Yeah. Right away.

946
00:56:34,200 --> 00:56:36,031
S-Say, Curly?

947
00:56:36,120 --> 00:56:38,918
-Yo!
-<i>Could you send up some water?</i>

948
00:56:39,000 --> 00:56:42,151
We're a little busy today, Walter,
tryin' to build a house.

949
00:56:42,240 --> 00:56:45,038
I'll get it myself.
I'll use my new stairs.

950
00:56:45,120 --> 00:56:46,951
<i>That's my boy.</i>

951
00:56:47,040 --> 00:56:49,349
Tar bucket comin' down.

952
00:56:54,720 --> 00:56:57,029
-Morning, James.
-Morning!

953
00:56:57,120 --> 00:56:59,395
-Alka-Seltzer.
-Just a minute.

954
00:56:59,480 --> 00:57:02,278
Any idea when you're going
to be finished here?

955
00:57:02,360 --> 00:57:04,191
-Two weeks.
-That's what I thought.

956
00:57:04,280 --> 00:57:06,157
Alka-Seltzer.
Here you go.

957
00:57:06,240 --> 00:57:09,391
Oh. You know you're almost out
of birth control pills?

958
00:57:10,680 --> 00:57:12,671
Thank you, James.

959
00:57:12,760 --> 00:57:15,115
Walter.
Walter!

960
00:57:15,200 --> 00:57:18,033
The water! I know.
I'm getting it.

961
00:57:19,520 --> 00:57:21,636
<i>[Whistles]</i>
<i>Hey, Walter!</i>

962
00:57:21,720 --> 00:57:24,678
You want this room painted blue,
like in the hallway?

963
00:57:24,760 --> 00:57:28,548
No, I do not. That's all wood...
What do you mean, "like the hallway"?

964
00:57:28,640 --> 00:57:30,471
The hallway.
Blue, right?

965
00:57:30,560 --> 00:57:32,198
I want nothing blue.
Nothing!

966
00:57:32,280 --> 00:57:35,795
Oh, man. Now I gotta go flush out
my paint sprayer.

967
00:57:35,880 --> 00:57:37,359
Oh, that's a bummer.

968
00:57:37,440 --> 00:57:40,910
-<i>## [Radio: Opera]</i>
-Have you seen Mr Fielding?

969
00:57:41,000 --> 00:57:42,831
-Fielding?
-Yeah.

970
00:57:42,920 --> 00:57:45,388
Don't know any Fieldings
around here. In Cincinnati...

971
00:57:45,480 --> 00:57:47,391
Walter?

972
00:57:47,480 --> 00:57:50,040
Oh, Walter!
Yeah, Walter.

973
00:57:50,120 --> 00:57:53,271
He was supposed to bring me
a bucket of water.

974
00:57:53,360 --> 00:57:55,590
-Bring you some water?
-Yeah. Do... No...

975
00:57:55,680 --> 00:57:57,511
-Ohh! Ohh!
-How's that?

976
00:57:57,600 --> 00:58:00,239
[Laughs]
It's a miracle.

977
00:58:00,320 --> 00:58:03,596
[Continues Laughing]
Yeah!

978
00:58:04,040 --> 00:58:05,519
## [Ranchero]

979
00:58:05,600 --> 00:58:07,431
Walter.

980
00:58:08,960 --> 00:58:12,396
-I wanna ask you something.
You're a lawyer, right?
-Yeah.

981
00:58:12,480 --> 00:58:15,597
Last year my father
was hit in the head by a golf ball.

982
00:58:15,680 --> 00:58:18,672
-<i>## [Radio: Pop]</i>
-Oh, can I unplug...

983
00:58:18,760 --> 00:58:20,273
Now, he seemed okay...

984
00:58:20,360 --> 00:58:22,669
but last week
we were watching TV...

985
00:58:22,760 --> 00:58:26,070
and I put on the Bob Hope
Desert Classic from Palm Springs.

986
00:58:26,160 --> 00:58:27,991
He goes friggin' nuts!

987
00:58:28,080 --> 00:58:29,911
My father, not Bob Hope.

988
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:33,197
So he kicks in
the friggin' TV screen. Now...

989
00:58:33,280 --> 00:58:35,669
<i>## [Pop Continues]</i>

990
00:58:39,640 --> 00:58:42,791
I'd have to study it, but I'd say you got
a great case against Bob Hope.

991
00:58:42,880 --> 00:58:44,518
Thanks, man.

992
00:58:50,880 --> 00:58:52,836
[Saw Buzzing]

993
00:58:56,760 --> 00:58:58,637
Aaah!

994
00:59:02,120 --> 00:59:04,475
<i>## [Opera Continues]</i>

995
00:59:13,760 --> 00:59:16,115
## [Bluegrass]

996
00:59:21,640 --> 00:59:23,517
## [Continues]

997
00:59:26,600 --> 00:59:29,433
## [Opera]

998
00:59:40,640 --> 00:59:43,200
<i>## [Opera Continues]</i>

999
01:00:01,480 --> 01:00:03,914
[Shouting, Screaming]

1000
01:00:19,520 --> 01:00:21,750
<i>## [Opera Continues]</i>

1001
01:00:51,200 --> 01:00:53,714
<i>## [Opera: Finale]</i>

1002
01:00:58,720 --> 01:01:01,837
-That was not so bad.
-<i>[Musicians Laughing]</i>

1003
01:01:01,920 --> 01:01:05,993
-<i>[Man] Are you happy with that one?</i>
-I am not unhappy with it.

1004
01:01:06,080 --> 01:01:09,311
<i>It's the best that miserable symphony</i>
<i>has ever sounded.</i>

1005
01:01:09,400 --> 01:01:13,029
You have my congratulations,
and you may go home.

1006
01:01:13,120 --> 01:01:15,918
-[Murmuring, Chattering]
-But don't you want to hear it back?

1007
01:01:16,000 --> 01:01:19,276
No, if there's something wrong
with it it's your fault...

1008
01:01:19,360 --> 01:01:21,794
and you will hang for it.

1009
01:01:21,880 --> 01:01:23,711
Do you have
a cigarette?

1010
01:01:23,800 --> 01:01:25,631
I'm sorry.

1011
01:01:32,960 --> 01:01:34,791
It was beautiful,
Max.

1012
01:01:34,880 --> 01:01:36,871
Better than Szell's version?

1013
01:01:36,960 --> 01:01:40,555
Mmm, I wondered why you did this.
I know you never liked it.

1014
01:01:40,640 --> 01:01:42,949
Well?

1015
01:01:43,040 --> 01:01:45,349
-It was better.
-Thank you.

1016
01:01:45,440 --> 01:01:48,238
It's a pity
that son of a bitch isn't alive...

1017
01:01:48,320 --> 01:01:51,118
because it would kill him
to hear that.

1018
01:01:51,200 --> 01:01:53,031
Have you got
a cigarette?

1019
01:01:53,120 --> 01:01:54,951
You stopped smoking
five years ago.

1020
01:01:55,040 --> 01:01:56,871
I started again
two weeks ago.

1021
01:01:56,960 --> 01:01:59,269
Can I have
the damn cigarette?

1022
01:01:59,360 --> 01:02:01,191
Mmm.
Filters.

1023
01:02:06,720 --> 01:02:09,439
You seem a little tense.

1024
01:02:09,520 --> 01:02:12,318
Your shoulders are up
over your ears.

1025
01:02:12,400 --> 01:02:15,472
-<i>Are you all right?</i>
-Don't I look all right?

1026
01:02:15,560 --> 01:02:17,391
In a word, no.

1027
01:02:17,480 --> 01:02:20,790
The only good part of our divorce
was that it seemed to make you happy.

1028
01:02:20,880 --> 01:02:23,917
For you to be without me
<i>and</i> unhappy...

1029
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:25,831
is such a waste.

1030
01:02:25,920 --> 01:02:29,037
You are making me sad.

1031
01:02:29,120 --> 01:02:31,156
Walter's
in Philadelphia...

1032
01:02:31,240 --> 01:02:35,199
and the idea of going back
to that house, alone...

1033
01:02:35,280 --> 01:02:37,589
Oh, God.

1034
01:02:37,680 --> 01:02:41,355
Why don't we have dinner
and a huge amount of alcohol?

1035
01:02:41,440 --> 01:02:43,908
I'm not dressed
for a restaurant.

1036
01:02:44,000 --> 01:02:47,754
My place.
Our old place.

1037
01:02:47,840 --> 01:02:50,638
-You can have a hot bath.
-[Sighs]

1038
01:02:50,720 --> 01:02:54,599
We'll have a fire. Hwang will make
anything you want for dinner.

1039
01:02:54,680 --> 01:02:56,557
-Duck I'orange.
-[Chuckles]

1040
01:02:56,640 --> 01:02:58,710
Twelve-year-old scotch.

1041
01:02:58,800 --> 01:03:00,631
In clean glasses.

1042
01:03:00,720 --> 01:03:02,631
That can be arranged.

1043
01:03:02,720 --> 01:03:04,551
I'm not going to bed
with you.

1044
01:03:04,640 --> 01:03:06,517
I may not ask you.

1045
01:03:24,000 --> 01:03:25,877
[Sighs]

1046
01:03:29,600 --> 01:03:31,431
Oh, my God.

1047
01:03:31,520 --> 01:03:33,351
Good morning.

1048
01:03:33,440 --> 01:03:35,476
-Oh, my God.
-What's wrong?

1049
01:03:35,560 --> 01:03:38,358
What happened?
What did we do?

1050
01:03:38,440 --> 01:03:41,238
-What have we done? Oh, my God!
-Calm down.

1051
01:03:41,320 --> 01:03:44,232
-You were a little looped.
You sang a few songs.
-The Beatles?

1052
01:03:44,320 --> 01:03:46,550
-The entire catalogue.
-What else?

1053
01:03:46,640 --> 01:03:49,438
-You don't remember?
-It was duck for dinner. Right?

1054
01:03:49,520 --> 01:03:52,318
-Followed by crepe Suzettes.
-I don't remember the crepe Suzettes.

1055
01:03:52,400 --> 01:03:54,231
-You don't remember the piano?
-No.

1056
01:03:54,320 --> 01:03:56,629
-<i>Under</i> the piano?
-I don't wanna hear any more.

1057
01:03:56,720 --> 01:03:58,950
-It was incredible. Better than Zurich.
-<i>Zurich?</i>

1058
01:03:59,040 --> 01:04:01,838
-The police came.
You don't remember any of this?
-<i>Oh, no.</i>

1059
01:04:01,920 --> 01:04:03,751
My shoe!

1060
01:04:03,840 --> 01:04:07,276
-<i>Not my shoe!</i>
-Last night you were
the animal I remember.

1061
01:04:07,360 --> 01:04:10,636
-<i>I don't need shoes!</i>
-Come back to me, and the police
will come every night.

1062
01:04:10,720 --> 01:04:12,551
-I love you.
-<i>This is a nightmare.</i>

1063
01:04:12,640 --> 01:04:14,471
Last night you said
you loved me...

1064
01:04:14,560 --> 01:04:17,358
that we would be together
the rest of our lives.

1065
01:04:17,440 --> 01:04:19,271
<i>I wasn't drunk,</i>
<i>I was insane!</i>

1066
01:04:19,360 --> 01:04:21,191
-When are you going to tell Walter?
-<i>Never!</i>

1067
01:04:21,280 --> 01:04:25,034
-You're just going to walk out
on him without saying anything?
-<i>I am not walking out on him.</i>

1068
01:04:25,120 --> 01:04:27,429
I am in love with him.
Not you, him.

1069
01:04:27,520 --> 01:04:30,318
-No, this whole wonderful realization
has confused you.
-<i>Oh!</i>

1070
01:04:30,400 --> 01:04:32,914
Talk this over with Walter,
and you'll see.

1071
01:04:33,000 --> 01:04:35,798
-Lying.
-What?

1072
01:04:35,880 --> 01:04:38,678
<i>I'm going to have to do</i>
<i>a lot of lying.</i>

1073
01:04:38,760 --> 01:04:41,558
-No. Tell him the truth.
-I'll lose him.

1074
01:04:41,640 --> 01:04:44,677
-Hey, take a chance.
-<i>[Door Slams]</i>

1075
